== A generalized method that works for higher-limit temperaments ==
If you need to do this process for a higher dimensionality than 6, then you'll need to understand how I found the symbols for each cell of Figure 2. Here's how:

# Take the rank, halved, rounded up. In our case, {{nowrap|&lceil;{{frac|''r''|2}}&rceil; {{=}} &lceil;{{frac|2|2}}&rceil;}} =&nbsp;&lceil;1&rceil; =&nbsp;1. Save that result for later. Let’s call it ''x''.
# Find the lexicographic combinations of ''r'' primes again: (2,&nbsp;3), (2,&nbsp;5), (3,&nbsp;5). Except this time we don’t want the primes themselves, but their indices in the list of primes. So: (1,&nbsp;2), (1,&nbsp;3), (2,&nbsp;3).
# Take the sums of these sets of indices, and to each sum, also add ''x''. So {{nowrap|[1 + 2 + ''x''|1 + 3 + ''x''|2 + 3 + ''x'']}} {{nowrap|{{=}} [1 + 2 + 1|1 + 3 + 1|2 + 3 + 1]}} {{nowrap|{{=}} [4, 5, 6]}}.
# Even terms become +'s and odd terms become −'s.

